com.thinkaurelius.titan.core
Interface TitanType

All Superinterfaces:
com.tinkerpop.blueprints.Element, TitanElement, TitanVertex, com.tinkerpop.blueprints.Vertex
All Known Subinterfaces:
TitanKey, TitanLabel
public interface TitanType
extends TitanVertex

TitanType defines the schema for TitanRelation. TitanType can be configured through TypeMaker to provide data verification, better storage efficiency, and higher retrieval performance.
Each TitanRelation has a unique type which defines many important characteristics of that relation.

  • Functional: Defines relations of this type to be functional (isFunctional()
  • Simple: Defines relations of this type to NOT have incident properties which provides better storage efficiencies in case properties are not needed. (isSimple()
  • Groups: Types can be grouped together for faster retrieval (getGroup()

TitanTypes are constructed through TypeMaker which is accessed in the context of a TitanTransaction via TitanTransaction.makeType().
TitanType names must be unique in a graph database. Many methods allow the name of the type as an argument instead of the actual type reference.

Author:
Matthias Bröcheler (me@matthiasb.com);

isFunctional

boolean isFunctional()
Checks whether this type is functional. A type is functional, if its relation instances are functional in the mathematical sense. A relation is functional iff each object in the domain has at most one value. Specifically, this means:
  • A property key is functional, if a vertex has at most one value associated with the key. Social security number is an example of a functional property key since each person has at most SSN.
  • An edge lable is functional, if a vertex has at most one outgoing edge for that label. Father is an exmaple of a functional edge label, since each person has at most one father.

Returns:
true, if the type is functional, else false

isModifiable

boolean isModifiable()
Checks whether relations of this type are modifiable after creation. TitanType can be designated non-modifiable which means all of its relation instances cannot be modified after creation.

Returns:
true, if relations of this type are modifiable, else false.

isSimple

boolean isSimple()
Checks whether relations of this type are simple. If a TitanType is simple, all of its relations are defined to be simple, which means that they do not accept incident properties. Simple relations are more storage efficient.

Returns:
true, if relations of this type are simple, else false.

getGroup

TypeGroup getGroup()
Returns the type group of this type. TitanTypes can be grouped together which makes it more efficient to retrieve all relations associated with the type group.

Returns:
type group of this type.
